1 Section 1. NRS 213.020 is hereby amended to read as follows:
2 213.020 1. Any person intending to apply to have a fine or
3 forfeiture remitted, a punishment commuted, a pardon granted or his
4 or her civil rights restored, or any person acting on his or her behalf,
5 must submit an application to the Board, in accordance with the
6 procedures established by the Secretary pursuant to NRS 213.017,
7 specifying therein:
8 (a) The court in which the judgment was rendered;
9 (b) The amount of the fine or forfeiture, or the kind or character
10 of punishment;
11 (c) The name of the person in whose favor the application is to
12 be made;
13 (d) The particular grounds upon which the application will be
14 based; and
15 (e) Any other information deemed relevant by the Secretary.
16 2. A person must not be required to pay a fee to have a fine or
17 forfeiture remitted, a punishment commuted, a pardon granted or his
18 or her civil rights restored pursuant to this section.
19 3. Except as otherwise provided in a policy adopted pursuant to
20 NRS 213.035, the Secretary shall submit notice of the date, time and
21 location of the meeting to consider the application and one copy of
22 the application to the district attorney [and to the district judge] of
23 the county wherein the person was convicted. In cases of fines and
24 forfeitures, notice of the date, time and location of the meeting to
25 consider the application must also be served on the chair of the
26 board of county commissioners of the county wherein the person
27 was convicted.
28 4. Except as otherwise provided in a policy adopted pursuant to
29 NRS 213.035, notice of the date, time and location of a meeting to
30 consider an application pursuant to this section must be served upon
31 the appropriate persons as required in this section at least 30 days
32 before the presentation of the application, unless a member of the
33 Board, for good cause, prescribes a shorter time.
34 5. Nothing in this chapter shall be construed to prohibit a
35 district judge from providing factual and non-character testimony
36 regarding the release or detention of a prisoner in response to a
37 subpoena or other formal request from the Board.
